Meta-Prompt.user:
Analyze the dataset below using the structural meta-framework defined here. This framework specifies HOW to reason — it is example-agnostic and applies to any tabular dataset.

[DATASET]
{data_sample}

[META-FRAMEWORK: Compositional Data Analysis]

{{
  "Task": "Exploratory data analysis with ranked insights",
  "Procedure": {{
    "Step 1 — Structural Decomposition": "Identify: number of rows and columns, data types per column, target variable (if any), and schema. Report exact values.",
    "Step 2 — Descriptive Synthesis": "For every relevant column compute or estimate: count, mean/median, min/max, null count, and cardinality. Always use numbers.",
    "Step 3 — Pattern Extraction": "Cross-examine categorical × numerical relationships to surface the strongest patterns. Rank findings by effect size or magnitude.",
    "Step 4 — Anomaly and Limitation Scan": "Flag missing values, outliers, data quality issues, and any risks of over-interpreting a limited sample.",
    "Step 5 — Insight Composition": "Synthesize Steps 1-4 into a ranked insight list. Each insight must cite at least one specific statistic from the data.",
    "Step 6 — Recommendations": "Derive exactly 3 actionable recommendations that are directly tied to the findings, not generic advice."
  }},
  "Output Schema": {{
    "Dataset Overview": "[1-2 sentences: rows × columns, key columns, target variable]",
    "Key Statistics": "[bullet list — one row per column, numbers only]",
    "Top Patterns": "[ranked bullet list, highest impact first]",
    "Anomalies and Limitations": "[bullet list — quality issues, sample risks]",
    "Top Insights": "[ranked, each backed by a concrete statistic]",
    "Recommendations": "[exactly 3 items, each tied to a specific finding]"
  }}
}}

Follow the Output Schema headings exactly. Do not add sections not listed above. Base every claim solely on the provided dataset.
